% â€” Pickup and bars 1-4 (bars counted from first full measure) â€”
% TEXTURE: S1+S2+A1+A2 only (TTBB tacet) â€” reduced opening
%
% Original Sop:  D4 | F4 E4 D4 | A4-A4 B4Âľ A4ÂĽ | F4 E4 D4 | F4 E4 (rest) E4
% S1 = Sop exactly
% S2 = thirds below Sop, diatonic: D4â†’B3, F4â†’D4, E4â†’C4(=C#4 in D maj key â†’ use C#? No â€” C in D major = C#)
%   Wait: D major scale = D E F# G A B C# D. So "C" in K:D = C#4, "D" = D4, etc.
%   The original S1V2 (alto) had: D4 | D4 D4 D4 | D4-D4 D4Âľ D4ÂĽ | D4 D4 D4 | D4 C#4 (rest) C4
%   Note: !accent!C in original alto = C4 natural? No â€” in K:D, C without accidental = C#4.
%   The original uses explicit accidentals for naturals. "C" in the key of D = C# unless marked =C.
%   So original S1V2 has C# on that accented beat. Fine â€” that's diatonic.
%   The ^G (G#) in bar 7 of the second line is the only non-diatonic inner voice note.
%
% S2: third below S1 in D major (diatonic thirds):
%   D4 â†’ B3 (third below); F#4 â†’ D4; E4 â†’ C#4; A4 â†’ F#4; B4 â†’ G4; G4 â†’ E4; C#5 â†’ A4; d5â†’B4
%
% A1: follows original alto (S1V2), which is diatonic except bar 7 (^G)
% A2: third below A1, diatonic
%
[V:1] [Q:1/4=120] D | F E D | A2 B3/4 A/4 | F E D | !accent!F !accent!E z E |
