%
% Bar 7 alto: E4 ^G4(=G#4) G4 â€” G# is non-diatonic in D major
%   Harmonic context: E3 E3 E3 in tenor + A2 A2 A2 in bass = E minor chord (ii of D)
%   G# makes it E major = secondary dominant V/vi (tonicizing B minor)
%   Rule: V/vi â†’ III or v (diatonic substitution)
%   Replace G# with G natural: E4 G4 G4 â†’ implies Em chord (ii minor) â€” diatonic, fine
%   Voice leading: E4â†’G4 is a minor third up, then G4 stays â†’ good
%
% T1 (written one octave higher than concert): A3 sounds â†’ write A; B3â†’B; D4â†’d; C#4â†’C (=C# in K:D)
